    <p>I'm 64. I hadn't heard of the 30-30-30 rule until recently — I don't spend much time on social media, and honestly that's where most of these trends live and die. But when I looked at the actual components, something interesting happened: the science held up better than I expected.</p>

    <p>Not perfectly. The 30-minute window claim is marketing, not physiology. But the underlying logic — protein in the morning, followed by movement — is exactly what the research on muscle preservation for men over 40 points toward. The trend got lucky and stumbled onto something real.</p>

    <p>Here's the honest breakdown of what works, what's overstated, and why the fasted workout advice you may have followed for years is worth reconsidering at this stage of life.</p>

