    <h2>What the 30-30-30 Rule Actually Is</h2>

    <p>The rule was popularized by fitness creator Gary Brecka and spread rapidly through social media. The premise: eat 30 grams of protein within 30 minutes of waking, then do 30 minutes of steady-state, low-intensity movement — a walk, a bike ride, something that doesn't spike your heart rate significantly.</p>

    <p>The claimed benefits range from fat loss to better energy to improved body composition. Some of those claims are well-supported. Others are stretched. Let's separate them.</p>

    <div class="verdict-box">
      <div class="verdict-label">Science Verdict — What Holds Up</div>
      <div class="verdict-grid">
        <div class="verdict-item">
          <div class="v-title yes">✓ 30g protein on waking</div>
          <p>Solid. Morning is when muscle protein synthesis is primed after the overnight fast. Hitting 30g early anchors your daily total and supports muscle maintenance.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="verdict-item">
          <div class="v-title yes">✓ Morning movement</div>
          <p>Genuinely beneficial. Low-intensity movement after a protein meal improves blood sugar regulation and produces measurable BDNF — supporting focus and mood.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="verdict-item">
          <div class="v-title no">✗ Strict 30-min window</div>
          <p>Overstated. The research supports a 1–2 hour window around training, not a 30-minute deadline. Missing the exact window won't undo the benefit.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="verdict-item">
          <div class="v-title no">✗ Magic fat-loss effect</div>
          <p>Overstated. The body composition benefits come from higher protein intake and consistent movement — not from the specific 30-minute timing sequence.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Why the Fasted Workout Advice Worked — And Why It Changes After 40</h2>

    <p>For a long time, the conventional wisdom was clear: train fasted in the morning, maximize fat oxidation, eat afterward. And for younger men or men with significant weight to lose, that logic isn't wrong. Fasted training does increase fat utilization during the workout itself. If fat loss is the primary goal, it has merit.</p>

    <p>But after 40, the equation shifts. The primary threat is no longer excess fat — it's <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/sarcopenia-men-over-40/" style="color: var(--green); font-weight: 600;">sarcopenia: the progressive loss of muscle mass</a> that accelerates in your 40s and 50s. And muscle protein synthesis — the process that maintains and rebuilds muscle — requires amino acids to be available during and after the training stimulus. Not 90 minutes later.</p>

    <p>When you train fasted and then eat, you're asking your body to both repair exercise-induced muscle damage and handle the incoming protein surge at the same time, with no amino acid support during the actual training window. For a 25-year-old with robust anabolic signaling, that's manageable. For a 50-year-old with blunted anabolic sensitivity, you're leaving muscle preservation gains on the table.</p>

