    <h2>The 30-Minute Window: What the Research Actually Says</h2>

    <p>This is where the trend oversimplifies. The concept of an "anabolic window" — a narrow post-workout period where protein timing is critical — was big in sports nutrition research in the 2000s. More recent meta-analyses have pulled that window open considerably. The current evidence supports eating protein within 1 to 2 hours of training, not within a strict 30-minute deadline.</p>

    <p>What does matter more than exact timing is <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/" style="color: var(--green); font-weight: 600;">total daily protein intake</a>. A man over 40 who consistently hits 120g per day with protein spread across meals will see better muscle preservation than one who obsesses over a 30-minute window but only hits 70g total. The window is real. The 30-minute cutoff is a simplification that spread because it's easy to remember.</p>

    <p>The practical takeaway: have your protein meal, then do your morning movement. If it's 45 minutes after you woke up instead of 28, nothing is lost.</p>

    <h2>The Movement Component: BDNF and Why It's Worth Keeping</h2>

    <p>The 30 minutes of low-intensity movement is arguably the most underappreciated part of this rule — and it's not primarily about calories burned.</p>

    <p>Morning movement, even at low intensity, triggers the release of BDNF — brain-derived neurotrophic factor. BDNF supports the growth and maintenance of neurons, and higher levels are associated with better memory, sharper focus, improved mood, and reduced risk of cognitive decline. For men over 40, this is not a small thing.</p>

    <p>The intensity question matters here. Low-intensity movement like a brisk walk does produce BDNF — measurably. But harder aerobic effort produces a larger spike. Current research suggests that lactate generated during moderate-to-vigorous exercise acts as a signaling molecule that amplifies BDNF release beyond what low-intensity movement achieves. So a 30-minute walk is genuinely beneficial. A 30-minute brisk walk or light jog is better for the BDNF effect specifically.</p>

    <p>There's also the blood sugar angle. A protein meal followed by light movement significantly improves postprandial glucose regulation — your blood sugar response after eating. For men over 40 with any concern about metabolic health or insulin sensitivity, this pairing has real clinical value beyond the trend.</p>

