    <!-- FAQ -->
    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">What is the 30-30-30 rule?</p>
        <p class="faq-a">The 30-30-30 rule means eating 30 grams of protein within 30 minutes of waking, followed by 30 minutes of low-intensity movement. It was popularized on social media as a morning routine for body composition and energy. For men over 40, the protein and movement components both have solid scientific backing — though the strict 30-minute timing window is less critical than the trend suggests.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">Should men over 40 do fasted workouts or eat protein first?</p>
        <p class="faq-a">For men over 40, eating protein before or shortly after training is generally better for muscle preservation than fasted training. Fasted workouts have merit for fat oxidation when younger or when weight loss is the primary goal — but after 40 the priority shifts to muscle protein synthesis, which requires amino acids available during and after the training stimulus.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">Does the 30-minute protein timing window actually matter?</p>
        <p class="faq-a">The 30-minute window is overstated. The science on protein timing is real — eating protein around training supports muscle protein synthesis — but the research supports a window of 1 to 2 hours, not a strict 30-minute deadline. Total daily protein intake matters far more than precise timing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">Does morning movement increase BDNF?</p>
        <p class="faq-a">Yes. Even low-intensity movement like a 30-minute walk produces measurable BDNF, supporting memory, focus, and mood. Higher-intensity aerobic exercise produces larger BDNF spikes — current research suggests lactate generated during harder efforts amplifies the effect. For men over 40, a brisk walk is genuinely beneficial for both cognition and blood sugar regulation after a protein meal.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

